data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0a49c1ade4142b490069a8c67aa5f48193a939c21b36a80da9","logprobs":[],"output_index":2,"sequence_number":340,"text":"Here are some of the most recent AI-related headlines and themes showing up in current reporting (as of Mar 4, 2026):\n\n- **AI regulation in the U.S. is hitting key federal deadlines (and may collide with state laws).** A recent legal analysis outlines looming March 2026 deadlines driven by a U.S. Executive Order on AI, including Commerce Department work evaluating “onerous” state AI laws and an FTC policy statement on how it will apply consumer-protection rules (FTC Act Section 5) to AI systems【6:1†source】.\n\n- **Courts and lawyers are still getting burned by “hallucinated” citations.** A Connecticut Supreme Court matter is reportedly facing a dismissal request after a legal brief included AI-generated false citations/quotes that weren’t verified by counsel—an example of ongoing risks when AI is used in legal workflows without rigorous checking【6:0†source】.\n\n- **Big Tech is pushing AI deeper into shopping and consumer decision-making.** Meta is reported to be testing an **AI shopping research** feature in its chatbot, positioning it against similar capabilities in ChatGPT and Google Gemini and signaling more competition around “AI as a shopping/research assistant”【6:0†source】.\n\n- **Research focus: long-context and new architectures.** One AI news roundup highlights Google Research papers introducing **Titans** (a new architecture) and **MIRAS** (a framework) aimed at improving long-context AI capabilities【6:4†source】.\n\nIf you tell me whether you care most about **product launches**, **research breakthroughs**, **regulation**, or **business/investing**, I can narrow this into a tighter “top 5” for that angle."}

